04619nam a22005655i 9780822397311DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20002000ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223973117 a10.1515/97808223973112doi  a(DE-B1597)554658  a(OCoLC)1151097517  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS731.M5bS3 2000 7aSOC0200002bisacsh04a305.895/9422211 aSchein, Louisa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMinority Rules :bThe Miao and the Feminine in China's Cultural Politics /cLouisa Schein. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2000] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b42 b&w photographs, 1 table, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBody, Commodity, Text00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1 Introduction -- tPart I Nation/ Representation -- t2 Of Origins and Ethnonyms Contested Histories, Productive Ethnologies -- t3 Making Minzu The State, the Category, and the Work -- t4 Internal Orientalism Gender and the Popularization of China's Others -- t5 Reconfiguring the Dominant -- tPart II Identity and Cultural Struggle -- t6 Songs for Sale Spectacle from Mao to Market -- t7 Scribes, Sartorial Acts, and the State Calling Culture Back -- t8 Displacing Subalternity The Mobile Other -- t9 Performances of Minzu Modernity -- t10 Conclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMinority Rules is an ethnography of a Chinese people known as the Miao, a group long consigned to the remote highlands and considered backward by other Chinese. Now the nation's fifth largest minority, the Miao number nearly eight million people speaking various dialects and spread out over seven provinces. In a theoretically innovative work that combines methods from both anthropology and cultural studies, Louisa Schein examines the ways Miao ethnicity is constructed and reworked by the state, by non-state elites, and by the Miao themselves, all in the context of China's postsocialist reforms and its increasing exchange and fascination with the West. She offers eloquently argued interventions into debates over nationalism, ethnic subjectivity, and the ethnography of the state.Posing questions about gender, cultural politics, and identity, Schein examines how non-Miao people help to create Miao ethnicity by depicting them as both feminized keepers of Chinese tradition and as exotic others against which dominant groups can assert their own modernity. In representing and consuming aspects of their own culture, Miao distance themselves from the idea that they are less than modern. Thus, Schein explains, everyday practices, village rituals, journalistic encounters, and tourism events are not just moments of cultural production but also performances of modernity through which others are made primitive. Schein finds that these moments frequently highlight internal differences among the Miao and demonstrates how not only minorities but more generally peasants and women offer a valuable key to understanding China as it renegotiates its place in the global order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aEthnic relationsxPolitical aspects. 0aHmong (Asian people)zChinaxSocial life and customs. 0aHmong (Asian people)zChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Minority Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822397311zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822397311423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822397311.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  